I must admit that, despite being a fan of all things fusion, Iâve never stayed in a post-room apartment before. The owner has fearlessly mixed up the functions of spaces which, until now, had seemed discreteâ¦.

With an imperious screech, the apartment front âdoorâ opens straight into the master bedroom - although one could be forgiven for failing to notice this at first, with the artful placement of two enormous, broken fridge freezers in the middle of the room. 

At the other end of this room, a sliding door opens to reveal another bedroom; as before, replete with a fine selection of the best bedding the US Penal System can offer. 

The dining room doubles as a kitchen and third bedroom (the sofa bed is in the guest suite, but doesnât really open out fully in there) - with a dresser, a thing made of wood, and three tables - one of which features a state of the art microwave as its central point and focal feature, something which is assured to dominate the conversation, and dictate the seating arrangements, of dinnertime.

The local area has some great bars, and I was able to overcome my doubts about sleeping in a bed surrounded by the looming silhouettes of two enormous, broken fridge freezers. In fact, I slept like a log, even forgetting to plug my phone in - thankfully the upstairs neighbourâs decision to renovate his entire flat at 9am saved me the annoyance of losing a precious day in New York to a lie-in, and luckily this was no one-off!

We asked the Landlord why there were, indeed, two enormous, broken fridge freezers in the middle of the room, he replied simply that they should be gone by the end of the week. Whatever that meant. When we asked if there was any way we could not be woken at the crack of dawn every single day by power-tools, he pointed out that they didnât start their interminable racket until about 9/10am. Which is obviously fine, thereâs little to no danger of a holidaymaker waking up with a hangover or anything.

Itâs in layout and styling that the apartment really comes into its own, though. There were no two matching pieces of furniture that we could find anywhere in this apartment, and this can only be a deliberate, stylistic choice on the part of the visionary who decorated this place (technically, the curtain rails match, but only one has any rings and neither has any curtain). From these touches, to the second bin in the middle of the room for no massively apparent reason, your visit will be full of surprises.

...the snappy 40-digit wi-fi password is actually longer than most non-NASA cameras will resolve in one image, but donât worry because itâs not on the router or anything. The landlord (or cleaner? Letâs just say it was someone who was there) handily shows you a picture on his phone, of which you can take a picture. One imagines the original password sticker festering somewhere in a cupboard, ageing as its picture does not: the portrait of Dorian G6A733WAFQ7FVN12 (not the actual code).


In summary - if you want somewhere with literally no frills, to sleep (renovations notwithstanding), have a wash and use the toilet, itâs fine. If you want somewhere to prepare food or host people, I wouldnât get your hopes up. Itâs also worth noting that in order to get to and from the front-room/kitchen or toilet, one must walk through all of the bedrooms - if youâre going in a mixed sex group, or youâre planning to have any, hilarity will doubtless ensue.
